# 7.4 Missing values

# If youve encountered unusual values in your dataset, and simply want to move on to the rest of your analysis, you have two options.
#1.  Drop the entire row with the strange values:
diamonds2 <- diamonds %>% 
  filter(between(y, 3, 20))
#2. Instead, I recommend replacing the unusual values with missing values. The easiest way to do this is to use mutate() to replace the variable with a modified copy. You can use the ifelse() function to replace unusual values with NA:
diamonds2 <- diamonds %>% 
  mutate(y = ifelse(y < 3 | y > 20, NA, y)) 
?ifelse
ggplot(data = diamonds2, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) + 
  geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 9 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(data = diamonds2, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) + 
  geom_point(na.rm = TRUE)

  ) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(sched_dep_time)) +

  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut))

  geom_freqpoly(mapping = aes(colour = cut), binwidth = 500)

  geom_boxplot()

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = class, y = hwy)) +
  geom_boxplot()

#To make the trend easier to see, we can reorder class based on the median value of hwy:
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = reorder(class, hwy, FUN = median), y = hwy))

# flip
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = reorder(class, hwy, FUN = median), y = hwy)) +
  coord_flip()
